pull_request.title: Test using a bit vector for storage instead of bytes
pull_request.body:
In the bitslice-based implementation, bits are stored in `[]byte`s, with each byte in the slice storing either a `0` or a `1`. Each bitslice is therefore taking up 7 times more space than necessary.

In this branch we try implementing a vector/slice of bits, where bits are still stored in `[]byte`s, but a byte holds 8 bits.

Preliminary results show that the bitslice-based implementation, while massively inefficient in its storage, is faster than the bit vector approach, by almost 2 orders of magnitude.

pull_request.title: feat(source): add new OffsetSource
pull_request.body:
Based on #228 so I could use the helpers in the examples, as the closures unfortunately can't detect the type they'll be called on.

I'm very open to suggestions on how to improve the usability here. I want the functionality for some personal projects where I gather configuration from various sources I don't control. Rather than trying to manipulate the data into the right format, it seems like it would be useful to have an option to load the data directly into the right place.

As per the examples provided, this can also be useful to load configuration that is _likely_ to be shared into multiple locations and then allow overriding them as needed.
